<h2>
    <strong>Introduction to Coho Salmon Fishing in Oregon</strong>
</h2>
<h3>
    <strong>What Are Coho Salmon?</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Coho salmon, also known as Silver salmon, are a prized species for sport fishing in Oregon. They typically weigh between 8 and 12 pounds, though some can exceed 15 pounds. Known for their acrobatic fights and delicious meat, Coho are a favorite among both recreational and subsistence fishers.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>Differences Between Coho and Chinook</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    While both are Pacific salmon species, Coho differ from Chinook in several ways:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Size:</strong> Coho are generally smaller than Chinook.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Appearance:</strong> Coho have brighter silver sides and a more pronounced hooked jaw (kype) during spawning.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Behavior:</strong> Coho often swim closer to shore and can be easier to catch from the bank.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>Why Gresham is a Hotspot</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Gresham’s location near the confluence of key Coho rivers makes it a strategic base for anglers. Within 30 minutes, you can access multiple productive streams, ensuring flexibility depending on river flow, run timing, and crowd levels.
</p>
<h2>
    <strong>Seasonal Timing for Coho Runs</strong>
</h2>
<h3>
    <strong>Best Months to Fish</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    The primary Coho salmon run in Oregon typically occurs between <strong>late August and early November</strong>. Peak fishing times around Gresham are usually in <strong>September and October</strong>.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>Early vs Late Runs</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Early Run Coho:</strong> Often smaller in size but more aggressive.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Late Run Coho:</strong> Larger and more mature, but sometimes more cautious and selective.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>Impact of Weather Patterns</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Rainfall plays a vital role in salmon migration. Heavy rain can swell rivers and encourage salmon to move upstream, making timing your trip with a fresh rainfall especially strategic.
</p>
