</h2>
<h3>
    <strong>Preferred Water Temperatures</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Coho salmon thrive in waters ranging from <strong>50°F to 58°F</strong>. They become less active when the temperature exceeds 60°F or falls below 45°F, so monitoring water conditions can significantly impact your success.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>Migration Patterns</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Coho typically begin their upriver migration from the ocean in <strong>late summer</strong>, triggered by changes in water temperature and flow. They travel from the Columbia River into tributaries like the Sandy River, often holding in deep pools or slow eddies during their upstream journey.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>Feeding Habits</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    While adult Coho stop feeding once they enter freshwater, they remain aggressive and will strike at flashy or erratic lures, especially during early stages of their migration.
</p>
<h2>
